Question: In LaTeX, which of the following methods correctly aligns the subscripts of multiple summation symbols to be at the same height?

A) Using the \limits command:
   \sum\limits_{i \in X} \sum\limits_{i \in \bar{X}}

B) Using the mathtools package and \adjustlimits command:
   \usepackage{mathtools}
   \adjustlimits\sum_{i \in X}\sum_{i \in \bar{X}}

C) Using the amsmath package and \substack command:
   \usepackage{amsmath}
   \sum_{\substack{i \in X}} \sum_{\substack{i \in \bar{X}}}

D) Using the align environment:
   \begin{align}
   \sum_{i \in X} & \sum_{i \in \bar{X}}
   \end{align}

Correct Answer: B

Explanation: The correct method to align the subscripts of multiple summation symbols at the same height is to use the mathtools package and its \adjustlimits command. This package provides a solution specifically designed for this purpose. Option A (\limits) doesn't solve the alignment issue. Option C (\substack) is used for multi-line subscripts and doesn't address the alignment problem. Option D (align environment) is used for equation alignment and doesn't specifically target subscript alignment in summations.

