Question: In LaTeX, which combination of commands would correctly implement local section numbering in the table of contents and section headings, while maintaining global section numbering in headers and cross-references?

A) \renewcommand{\thesection}{\arabic{section}}
   \renewcommand{\sectionmark}[1]{\markright{\thechapter.\thesection\ #1}}

B) \renewcommand{\thesection}{\thechapter.\arabic{section}}
   \renewcommand{\sectionmark}[1]{\markright{\arabic{section}\ #1}}

C) \renewcommand{\thesection}{\arabic{section}}
   \renewcommand{\sectionmark}[1]{\markright{\arabic{section}\ #1}}

D) No combination of these commands can achieve the desired result; a custom package is required.

Correct Answer: A

Explanation: Option A is correct because it uses \renewcommand{\thesection}{\arabic{section}} to set local numbering for sections in the table of contents and section headings, while \renewcommand{\sectionmark}[1]{\markright{\thechapter.\thesection\ #1}} ensures global numbering (including chapter number) in headers. This combination achieves local scope where needed and global scope in headers and cross-references. Option B incorrectly uses global numbering for \thesection. Option C uses local numbering in headers, which is not desired. Option D is incorrect because the desired result can be achieved with LaTeX commands without requiring a custom package.

